{{Infobox language |name=Azha |nativename= |states=[[China]] |speakers=53,000 |date=2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Lolo-Burmese languages|Lolo-Burmese]] |fam3=[[Loloish languages|Loloish]] |fam4=[[Southeastern Loloish|Southeastern]] |fam5=Sani–Azha |iso3=aza |glotto=azha1235 |glottorefname=Azha}}
'''Azha''' is one of the [[Loloish languages]] spoken by the [[Yi people]] of [[China]].
==Innovations== In Azha, the words for ‘goat’, ‘eat’, and ‘drink’ are innovative (Pelkey 2011:377). Luojiayi Azha<ref>The representative dialect studied in Pelkey (2011) is that of Luojiayi 倮家邑, Binglie Township 秉烈乡, [[Wenshan Zhuang and Miao Autonomous Prefecture]].</ref> mɛ³³xɛ³³ ‘goat’, la̠⁴⁵ ‘eat’, ŋɨ³³ ‘drink’ are not derived from Proto-Ngwi *(k)-cit<sup>L</sup> ‘goat’, *dza² ‘eat’, and *m-daŋ¹ ‘drink’.
==References== {{Reflist}} *Pelkey, Jamin. 2011. ''Dialectology as Dialectic: Interpreting Phula Variation''. Berlin: De Gruyter Mouton.
