{{Infobox language family
|name=Senagi 
|region=[[New Guinea]]
|familycolor=Papuan
|family=One of the world's primary [[language family|language families]]
|glotto=sena1264
|glottorefname=Senagi 
|child1=[[Angor language|Angor]]
|child2=[[Dera language|Dera]]
}}

The '''Senagi''' languages are a small independent [[language family|family]] of [[Papuan languages]] in the classification of [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]], that had been part of [[Stephen Wurm]]'s [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] proposal.

The Angor language is unusual in that it distinguishes gender in the second- and third-person [[dual (grammatical number)|dual]] and plural ''(you'' and ''they),'' but not in the singular. It is not clear if Dera does the same.

==Classification==
The Senagi family consists of only two languages:

* '''Senagi''' family: [[Angor language|Angor]], [[Dera language|Dera]]

The most promising external links are with the [[Sepik languages|Sepik]] and [[Torricelli languages|Torricelli]] languages. The pronoun for "I" is reconstructed as ''*wan'' for both proto-Senagi and proto-Sepik, while the Angor masculine dual and plural pronominal suffixes ''-fa-'' and ''-mu-'' appear to reflect the proto-Sepik and proto-Torricelli dual and plural pronominal suffixes ''*-p'' and ''*-m.''

